Introduction

In this exercise, you are supposed to work with a real life data set on your own. Therefore, I combined the Visa Network Data (link) with additional data from the Penn World Table 9.0 (link) and the PolityIV project (link). The data set visa.df (or the name you gave it using the assignment operator <-) entails the following variables:

Variable Description Origin
name The name of the country Visa Network Data (cleaned)
indegree The number of visa waiver a country is granted by other nations Visa Network Data (own computation)
outdegree The number of visa waivers a country gives to other country Visa Network Data (own computation)
year Year of the information All sources
polity2 A measure of countryâs democracy (+ 10: Full Democracy / -10: Autocracy) PolityIV project (link)
iso3 ISO3 country codes Package countrycode (link)
pop Countryâs population Penn World Table 9.0
hc Human Development Index Penn World Table 9.0
cgdpe Expenditure-side real GDP, using prices for final goods that are constant across countries Penn World Table 9.0
gdppc GDP per capita, using cgdpe / pop Penn World Table 9.0 (own computation)
continent Countryâs continent location Package countrycode (link)
region Countryâs region Package countrycode (link)

The data set is available on moodle. It is the same that we used during the last session. Hence, your script should start with loading the tidyverse library(tidyverse)1 and the data (readRDS()).

Question 1

In the session, we already learned that mobility rights (variable: indegree) are unequally distributed among continents (continent). We can check once more using the following code:

arrange(summarize(group_by(visa.df, continent), mean = mean(indegree), n()), desc(mean))
## # A tibble: 5 x 3
##   continent    mean `n()`
##       <chr>   <dbl> <int>
## 1    Europe 63.4359    39
## 2  Americas 42.5200    25
## 3   Oceania 40.0000     5
## 4      Asia 19.7234    47
## 5    Africa 14.5600    50

Asia and Africa are clearly behind in regard to mobility rights.

Please, replicate the code using the pipe-operator %>% in order to make it more user-friendly and accessible.

Question 2

Recode the variable gdppc into deciles. Then group the data by this variable and compute the mean indegree. Are gdppc and indegree related? You can also check the correlation between the variables (?cor).

Hints:

  1. Have a look at the function ntile or cut (rather go with ntile; it is easier).
  2. Try to remove the missing values beforehand !is.na().
